<subSubSection lastPageId="212" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="211" pageNumber="212" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="211.[151,1437,150,2013]" lastBlockId="212.[198,1437,150,321]" lastPageId="212" lastPageNumber="213" pageId="211" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[749,997,1914,1941]" pageId="211" pageNumber="212">Pacific Bluefin Tuna</emphasis>
. To 
<quantity box="[1051,1137,1915,1941]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.71" pageId="211" pageNumber="212" unit="cm" value="271.0">271 cm</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[1155,1219,1915,1942]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.71272" pageId="211" pageNumber="212" unit="ft" value="8.9">8.9 ft</quantity>
) FL (
<bibRefCitation author="Foreman and Ishizuka" firstAuthor="Foreman" pageId="211" pageNumber="212" pagination="181 - 186" refId="ref279831" refString="Foreman, T. J. Y. Ishizuka, Y. (1990) Giant bluefin tuna off southern California, with a new California size record. California Fish and Game, 76, 181 - 186." type="journal article" year="1990">Foreman and Ishizuka 1990</bibRefCitation>
). Western Pacific Ocean north to 
<collectingCountry box="[773,837,1951,1977]" name="Japan" pageId="211" pageNumber="212">Japan</collectingCountry>
(Nakabo in 
<bibRefCitation author="Nakabo" box="[992,1152,1951,1977]" firstAuthor="Nakabo" pageId="211" pageNumber="212" refId="ref304533" refString="Nakabo, T. (Ed.). (2002) Fishes of Japan with Pictorial Keys to the Species. Tokai University Press, Tokyo." type="book" year="2002">Nakabo 2002</bibRefCitation>
), southern Kuril Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Savinykh" box="[205,378,1987,2013]" firstAuthor="Savinykh" pageId="211" pageNumber="212" pagination="18 - 27" refId="ref320217" refString="Savinykh, V. F. (1998) Nekton composition of near-surface waters of the subarctic front zone in the northwest part of the Pacific Ocean according to the data of drift-net catches. Journal of Ichthyology, 38, 18 - 27." type="journal article" year="1998">Savinykh 1998</bibRefCitation>
), and southern Sea of Okhotsk; Shelikof Strait, Gulf of Alaska (Mecklenburg 
<emphasis box="[1236,1291,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="211" pageNumber="212">et al.</emphasis>
2002) to just inside southwest corner of Gulf of California (
<bibRefCitation author="Robertson and Allen" box="[724,1027,150,177]" firstAuthor="Robertson" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" refId="ref316799" refString="Robertson, D. R. and Allen, G. R. (2015) Shorefishes of the Tropical Eastern Pacific: an Information System. Version 2.0 (2008). Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute, Balboa. http: // biogeodb. stri. si. edu / sftep / en / pages" type="url" year="2015">Robertson and Allen 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Oceanic epipelagic; depth: surface to 
<quantity box="[229,324,187,213]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.426" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" unit="m" value="1426.0">1,426 m</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[340,433,187,214]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4255495999999999" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" unit="ft" value="4677.0">4,677 ft</quantity>
) (Kurt Schaefer, pers. comm. to M.L.). Previously considered a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Actinopterygii" family="Scombridae" genus="Thunnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thynnus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="212" pageNumber="213">Thunnus thynnus</emphasis>
(Linnaeus, 1758)
</taxonomicName>
, raised to full species status by 
<bibRefCitation author="Collette" box="[841,1014,223,249]" firstAuthor="Collette" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" pagination="149 - 164" refId="ref271119" refString="Collette, B. B. (1999) Mackerels, molecules, and morphology. In: Seret, B. &amp; Sire, J. - Y. (Eds.), Proceedings of the 5 th Indo- Pacific Fish Conference, Noumea-New Caledonia, 1997. Societe Francaise d'Ichtyologie, Paris, pp. 149 - 164." type="book chapter" year="1999">Collette (1999)</bibRefCitation>
. The size of more than 
<quantity box="[1276,1320,223,249]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" unit="m" value="3.0">3 m</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[1335,1390,223,250]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" unit="ft" value="10.0">10 ft</quantity>
) FL and weight of about 
<quantity box="[425,501,259,285]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="6.8" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" unit="kg" value="680.0">680 kg</quantity>
given by Mecklenburg 
<emphasis box="[764,820,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="212" pageNumber="213">et al.</emphasis>
(2002), after 
<bibRefCitation author="Collette and Nauen" box="[971,1268,259,285]" firstAuthor="Collette" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" refId="ref271377" refString="Collette, B. B. &amp; Nauen, C. E. (1983) FAO Species Catalogue. Volume 2. Scombrids of the World. FAO Fisheries Synopsis No. 125, Volume 2. FAO, Rome." type="book" year="1983">Collette and Nauen (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, pertains to the Atlantic species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[390,504,295,321]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Scombridae" genus="Thunnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thynnus">
<emphasis box="[390,504,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="212" pageNumber="213">T. thynnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
